{"/service/ndnp/lu/batch_lu_jacobi_ver01/data/sn88064250/00212475671/1907112301/0218.xml":{"full_text":"SIf You Will\no Call On Us!\nSou may meet the opportunity of your life in Real Estate investment likely to prove profitable within a shorter time\nthan you imagine. Our time, experience and facilities are at your disposal-on commission or a straight buying\nor selling basis.\nLittell Lawler,\nLand and Immigration Agents, Opelousas, Louiaiana.\nIl l II I e I H I a me II l l\nFINANCIAL PANICS\nAND THEIR CAUSES\nPicayune Deals Ably With the Subject Under\nCaption of \"Panic of 1893.\"\nWE ARE BUSINESS lAMBLERS\nCountry Passes Through Financial ConvulsIon\nAbout Once In Every Twenty Years--Pre\ndicts N. Y. Cash Payments by New Year\nThe New Orleans Picayune, in an\nexhaustive and comprehensive editor\nial in last Sunday's issue, deals at\nlength with financial panics, and par\nticularly that of 1893.\nIt says that in every instance where\nthe busines$ of this country has been\noverwhelmed by a financial panic, it\nhas been caused by excessive specula\ntion.\n\"The American people pass all\nothers as business gamblers,\" says\nthe Picayune. \"Some of them may\nemploy their leisure in betting on\nregular gambling games, but that is\na mere bagatelle. The money lost\nand won in that way is trivial in\namount in comparison with the vast\nsums staked in business speculations.\nThe desire to get rich quick is so\noverpowering that men who are ordi\nnaPily prudent become in a measure\ninsane when some scheme is presented\nby which it is shown with more or\nLock ten men in a room, and instantly a leader appears; one who dominates; one who can tell you The Reason Why.\nOpelousas is Growing, Growing, Growing. It is 'destined soon to become a Big City. Ask yourself\nSWHEN, WHAT AND WHERE IS THE liday\nBEST PLACE TO BUY YOUR Hiday oos.\nTHE LID IS OFF! THE BOTTOM DROPPED OUT!\nThe Prices are so low this year--way below your expectations at\n*Jacobs News Depot Company,\nOpposite Courthouse, Landry Street, OPELOUSAS, LA.\nSnothing can stop the trend of customers to our establishment. Our Goods, our Prices, wil! bring them every time. This year, way beyond the control of\nA lt any human agency, was the cotton crop failure, and the anticipated fifteen cent cotton, which made manufacturers, and others, ask fictitious, outrageous,\nunheard-of prices for their goods. The wise one--THE LEADER--DID NOT BUY. October came with a crash. The earth shook, the money market\nquivered, and goods were placed on the market at big discounts. That was the time, THEN AND THERE, to buy and WE BOUGHT We Iave began\ndisplaying NEW GOODS. Visit us once, and you will always be glad to call and see us again.\nSpecial. Special. Special.\nDuring this month we can and will save our customers money on the Magazines and Newspapers they read. Send us a list of the Magazines and Newspapers you want, and we will send yuo\nPrices and Catalog, FREE for the asking.\nEMMMERMMMMMMMAEMBERMMMMM MMAMM MMAMMA\nless plausibility that something can\nbe made out of nothing, or that im\nmense returns can be secured by\nmoderate or even small investments.\nAlmost any stranger, if he be a glib\ntalker and possesses impudently easy\nmanners, can secure listeners, no\nmatter how unreasonable and im\npossibie a proposition he may unfold.\"\nBut the chief gambling, goes on\nthe article, in which millions on\nmillions are risked is on what is\nclaimed to be in the line of legiti\nmate business. Men will take enor\nmous risks on the probabilities of the\nsize of the crops of staple products.\nSome will bet that the crops will be\ninsufficient to meet the demands for\nconsumption, and therefore prices\nwill go up, and they invest their\nmoney on the possibility. Others be\nlieving that the products in question\nwill be in unusual quantity, proceed\nto take risks on the consequent decline\nof' prices. Then there are others\nwho believe that the earnings of cor\nporations and trusts will be large or\notherwise as the case may be, and\nthey buy or sell the stocks of such\ncorporations on the faith of their\nforebodings. This produces no wealth,\nand does not add to the valuable pro\nducts of the country or increase the\namount of money, but on the contrary,\nswallows up the available cash that is\nneeded for the conduct and mainten\nance of regular business operations,\nand so causes a scarcity of money\nfor the most important purposes and\ncreates conditions that precipitate a\nfinancial panic by causing a loss of\nconfidence in banks and moneyed in\nstitutions.\nThe speculators in order to carry\non their deals must have money, and\nthey pay for it at rates which no\nregular'and necessary business can\nafford, and therefore the money is\nloaned out to the big speculators,\nwhile the bank vaults are deprived of\ncash, but are stuffed with the securi\nties deposited by the borrowers, and\nthese securities, however valuable in\nordinary times, can not be converted\ninto cash at a moment's notice.\nThis country has passed through a\ntremendous financial convulsion about\nonce in every twenty years or less.\nJust as soon as business recovers\nfrom the last panic speculation be\ngins again, and goes on until the\nfinances can no longer bear the pres\nsure. Then comes another panic.\nThe last before the present was that\nof 1893. It followed the one of\n1872, which prostrated the business\nthroughout the country. The coun\ntry was slow in recoverihg from the\ncrash of '73, but the revival com\nmenced in 1879 when railroad build\ning, which had nearly stopped under\nthe general depression that followed\nthe panic, was recommenced with\ngreat activity, so that in thirteen\nyears, from '79 to '93, the mileage\nwas doubled, having increased from\n86,500 to 175,100 miles. Business\nof every sort was correspondingly\ninflated, and the time had come for a\nfinancial convulsion.\nThe Picayune says that the New\nYork banks in 1893, after using\nClearing House certificates for four\nmonths, resumed money payments,\nand business was resumed on the\nusual basis. In consideration of the\nWhite Lily Restaurant\nLOUIS MINOR, Manager.\nOld Lacombe Hotel Cook.\nWe wish to call the attention of the public to the fact that we are\nnow opened in our new CHACHERE BUILDING on Court street, and are\nnow better prepared than ever to serve you. Give us a trial and be con\nvinced. Neat and polite waiters. Open from 5 g. m. to 2 a. m.\nSHORT ORDERS A SPECIALTY.\nSpecial Accommodation for Ladies. sept21\nh. W. Perry Co.\nHave opened A Jewelry Store in the old Isaac Store,\ncorner Main and North Streets. Fine line of Watches and\nJewelry. Watches, Clocks and Jewelry Repaired Promptly at\nModerate Prices. FINE WATCH REPAIRING A SPECIALTY.\nH. W. PERRY, of New York, Watch Maker. and Manager\nvast amount .of Government money\nabsorbed by them, they ought, this\ntime, to be able to, resume cash pay\nments at the beginning of the New\nYear. When New York banks un\nlock New Orleans money deposited in\ntheir vaults we can resume at once.\nWe apologize to the Picayune if\nits able and scientific article .has\nsuffered by being abridged by us, a\ncourse made necessary by the ex\ntreme length of the article in question.\nLand Offce at New Orleans, La.,\nNov. 2.1907.\nNotice is hereby given that FRANCOIS\nVIDRINE, JR., of Pine Prairie. La., has\nfiled notice of his intention to make final\nFive Year proof in support of his claim,\nviz: Homestead Antry No. 23806 made No\nvember 22, 1901, for the E\u00bd/ of SE/. Section\n28, Township 8 South, Range 1 West, La.\nMeridian. and that said proof will be made\nbefore John Evans, U. S. Com'r at Blanche,\nLa., on December 19, 1907\nHe names the following witnesses to prove\nhis continuous residence upon and cultiva\ntion of, the land, vis:\nJean Pierre Ardoin, of Pine Prairie, La.,\nCleophas Fontenot, of Beaver, La., Edward\nMcDaniel, of Beaver, La.. Esterlie Reid, of\nPine Prairie, La.\nWALTER L. COHEN,\nnov9-6t Register.\nFor Sale.\nHousehold Furniture, also a\nlot of Fine Milk Cows, s\nHorses;\nOne pair Creole Mules;\nA complete outfit of Black\nsmith tools and farming C\nimplements;\nOne Surry, One Buggy,\nOne Wagon;\nAnd many other articles too\nnumerous to mention.\nn16 EUGiENE LACHAPELLE.\nNotice.I will not be responsible for any\nNotice debts contracted by any memberof\nmy family, or anybody else, except myself\nor my wife, or our signatures.\nM. L. SWORDS.\nODelousas. La.. January 15. 1907. k\nSUCC\"ESSION SALE.\nESTATE OF ANNIE E. BRUMFIELD.\nNo. 6224, Probate Docket, District Court,\nParish of St. Landry, La.\nBy virtue of an order of the Hon. E. T.\nLewis, Judge of the 16th Judicial District\nCourt, in and for the Parish of St. Landry.\nState of Louisiana, dated October 41st,\n1907, there will be sold at public auction,\nto the last and highest bidder by the un\ndersigned natural tutor or any duly quall\nfled auctioneer at the last residence of, the\nsaid deceased on\nTuesday, Nov. 26, 1907,\nat 11 o'clock a. m., the following described\nproperty, belonging to the above estate,\nto-wit:\nAll that certain lot or parcel of land sit\nuated In the parish of St. Landry, La., and\ndescribed as follows, to-wit: East half of\nNorthwest quarter of Section Twenty-two,\nin township i, South of Range Two west\nin Southwestern Land District of Louisiana\ncontainingeighty and 81-100 acres, less one\nacre given to School House, leaving seven\nty:nine and 81-100 acres. Being the same\nproperty acquired by William L. Perry\nfrom Daniel Douget, Aug. 10th, 1901, as ap\npears recorded in Book X No. 8, page 69,\nClerk's office of the parish of St. Landry.\nTerms Cash.\nWILLIAM L. PERRY,.\noct26-5t Natural Tutor.\nS UCCESSION SALE.\nESTATE OF EMILIC WASHINGTON. SR.\nNo. Probate Docket, District Court,\nParish of St. Landry, La.\nBy virtue of an order of the Hon. E. T.\nLewis, Judge of the 16th Judicial District\nCourt, in and for the Parish of St. Landry,\nState of Louisiana. there will be sold at\npublic auction, to the last and highest bid\nder, by the undersigned administrator or\nany duly qualified auctioneer, at the last\nresidence of the deceased, in Plaisance.\nSt. Landry parish, La., on\nTuesday, Dec. 3, 1907,\nat 11 o'clock a. m., the following described\nproperty, belonging to the above estate,\nto-wit\nA certain plantation in Plaisance, this\nparish, measuring fifty arpents and\nbounded north by Bayou Carron and Union\nRice and Irrigation Company, south by\nEmile Washington Jr., east by W. D. Har\ngroder and west by W. D. Hargroder and\nUnion Rice and Irrigation Company.\nOne mule; three head horses;\nFour head horn cattle; one buggy;\nHousehold furniture, etc.\nTerm Cash.\nW. D. HARGRODER,\nnov2-5t Administrator.\nJohn N. Ogden,\nAttorney at Law,\nOffice on Bellevue street, near the mar\nket--lst floor in the Larcade building. Je15\nJ.. B.SANDOZ\nUNDERTAKER\nCOMPLET LINE OF\nCoffins, Cask'ets, Funeral\nRobes, Etc.\nFully Equipped with the latest style\nhearses. 'Phone 8\nMain Street Opelousas, La\nSHERIFF'S _ALE.\nOSCAR 8HANK8\nversus\nCHARtES W. KROTZ.\nNo. 17756, 16th Judicial District Court, St.\nLandry Parish, Lal\nBy virtue of a writ of Ileri faclas\nissued out of the Hon 16th Judicial Dis\ntrict Court, lt and for the parish of St. Lan\ndry, in the above entitled and numbered\nsuit, and to me directed. I have seized and\nwill offer for sale, at public auc\ntlol, to the last and highest bidder, at the\nfront door of the Court House o St. Landry\n,arish,in Opelousas, La., on\nSaturday, .Nov.' 30, 1907,\nat 11 O'clock a. m., the following described\nproperty, to-wit:\nSAll cf the right, title' and nhterest of\nCharles W. Krotz in and to the .Melville\nLand Company and the Melville Bldx and\nLumber Company, bothl being corporations\norganied under the laws of the State of\nDelaware, doing business in the State of\nLouisiana, and each having a legal office\nand domicile in the town of Melville, St.\nLandry parish, La.\nTerms Cash.\nM. L. SWORDS, Sheriff.\nNovember 15, 19 t.\nDR. J. B. HARVEY\nDENTIST\nGeneral Dental Practice.\nOffice: on North street, next to Evans'\nHardware store, Opelousas, La.","height":"24408","width":"17736"}}
